<div style="margin-left: 15%; margin-right: 15%;">
    <h1 class="my-5">How To Protect Database Inputs</h1>
    <div>
        <div>
            <p>
                A common mistake among young programmers is to not protect data inputs into a database.
                This can cause many issues for these novice programmers and their employers. An example
                of this is illustrated perfectly in this comic: https://xkcd.com/327/.
            </p>
            <p>
                When a programmer allows unsanitized input into a database then that data could be any
                string that a user has chosen. Which includes “Robert); DROP TABLE Students;”. If this raw
                string was entered into a SQL command, then the entire Students table would be dropped.
            </p>
            <p>
                In order to avoid this, the program needs to pass in a SQL parameter to the command instead
                of a raw string. I had to do this when I needed to add users to a database. At first,
                I put in the raw string into the database. Which looked something like this:
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center border border-danger py-3" style="width: 90%">
            <img src="~/Images/SQL/badDataInput.png" alt="badDataInput" style="width: inherit;">
        </div>        
        <p>
            Depending on the language being, the tools used to sanitize the data inputs might be different,
            the steps are generally the same.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <div>
                    Instantiate and open a connection:
                </div>
                <div class="text-center py-3">
